cs.LG, cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.SOC, cs.AI 

This paper proposes a data-driven framework for characterizing the long-term impact of algorithmic policies on reshaping the underlying population, which suggests it could belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), social and information networks (cs.SI), cybernetics (cs.CY), sociology (cs.SOC), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses the psychological and economic literature, which could further support its classification under cs.SOC and cs.AI.
